	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Petruza</b> [ Thu Mar 18, 2010 7:31 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>NOP taking many addressing modes, is that so?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hi, this doc: <a href="http://nesdev.com/6502_cpu.txt" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/6502_cpu.txt</a> cites NOP as having many addressing modes, thus taking different byte lengths and cycles.
<br />Is that so?
<br />
<br />In the other hand, this doc: <a href="http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html#NOP" class="postlink">http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html#NOP</a> cites NOP as having only one opcode ($EA, challenge everything, that's why I'm asking) being 1 byte long and consuming 2 cycles.
<br />
<br />So, what's the deal?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
