	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />AFAIK there is only one official NOP, the others are illegal opcodes, like LAX and many others.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>blargg</b> [ Thu Mar 18, 2010 10:10 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The other NOPs also do memory accesses and then discard the result. Not a problem unless it happens to access an I/O register with a side-effect.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Dwedit</b> [ Thu Mar 18, 2010 10:31 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Puzznic has a two-byte nop.  If you don't emulate it as a two byte nop (for instance, you treat all illegal instructions as a one byte nop), then the second byte is a BRK instruction, and that messes things up.
<br />
<br />Is Puzznic a bad dump?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


